[White "Cochrane Gambit"]
[Black "for Black: 5.Bc4+"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "Main Level"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "petroff-defense-cochrane-gambit/course/1519, variation/61441"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 {Petroff's Defense has a reputation, not entirely deserved, 
as a stodgy drawing weapon. The truth is that only a third of all Petroff games 
that last more than 20 moves are drawn. The high percentage of short Petroff 
draws in databases reflects the willingness of both sides to sign an early peace 
treaty.} 3. Nxe5 {White has a few options to bail out into a different opening, 
but the two main moves have always been either taking the pawn or playing an 
immediate d4.} d6 {The move 3...Nxe4!?, which is sometimes called the Damiano 
Defense, is better than its reputation, as Black does not have to fall into the 
classic trap and lose his Queen but can instead play the move as a pawn 
sacrifice. That said, d6 is the overwhelming choice at master level. It is also 
as solid as a rock.} 4. Nxf7 $5 {The Cochrane Gambit. In an era without computer 
analysis, this sort of sacrifice could terrorize would-be practitioners of the 
Petroff. Today, with both strong engines and large databases to give us a 
picture of GM praxis, it is possible to prepare against the Knight sac with 
confidence.} Kxf7 {There is no good way to decline this sacrifice, so Black 
should man up and learn the analysis required to obtain an advantage against 
it.} 5. Bc4+ $6 {Giving an immediate check looks aggressive. But it turns out 
that Black can meet that aggression with a pawn sacrifice that well and truly 
turns the tables.} d5 $1 {This is Black's only good move here, but it is a very 
good one. White does not want to exchange pieces on d5, as that would blunt his 
initiative. So he is virtually forced to take on d5 with his e-pawn.} 6. exd5 $1 
{The capture on d5 ends all White's dreams of a big center with pawns on d4, e5, 
and f4, and the pawn on d5 actually blocks White's own Bishop, giving Black the 
leisure to complete his development without harrassment.} Bd6 {The Bishop is 
better placed here than it would be on c5 (where it could be hit by d4). It is 
also standing directly in front of White's extra d-pawn, which means that White 
cannot give a discovered check for the foreseeable future.} 7. O-O {White 
scurries out of the way before Black can dislocate the King or deactivate 
White's pieces by...Re8+.} Rf8 {Now that White's King is off of the e-file, 
there is no great benefit to Black in putting his Rook there. While...Re8 would 
not be a terrible move, keeping the Rook on the f-file actually enhances Black's 
opportunities for a kingside attack of his own in some lines.} 8. h3 {Nipping 
any ideas of...Ng4 or...Bg4 in the bud.} Kg8 {Black completes the operation of 
castling by hand. Now Black's pieces can flow very naturally toward the White 
kingside with moves like...Bf5, ...Qe8-g6, and...Nbd7. White is seriously worse 
here.} *

