1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 {Petroff's Defense has a reputation, not entirely deserved, 
as a stodgy drawing weapon. The truth is that only a third of all Petroff games 
that last more than 20 moves are drawn. The high percentage of short Petroff 
draws in databases reflects the willingness of both sides to sign an early peace 
treaty.} 3. Nxe5 {White has a few options to bail out into a different opening, 
but the two main moves have always been either taking the pawn or playing an 
immediate d4.} d6 {The move Nxe5!?, which is sometimes called the Damiano 
Defense, is better than its reputation, as Black does not have to fall into the 
classic trap and lose his Queen but can instead play the move as a pawn 
sacrifice. That said, d6 is the overwhelming choice at master level. It is also 
as solid as a rock.} 4. Nxf7 $5 {The Cochrane Gambit. In an era without computer 
analysis, this sort of sacrifice could terrorize would-be practitioners of the 
Petroff. Today, with both strong engines and large databases to give us a 
picture of GM praxis, it is possible to prepare against the Knight sac with 
confidence.} Kxf7 {There is no good way to decline this sacrifice, so Black 
should man up and learn the analysis required to obtain an advantage against 
it.} 5. Nc3 {Strictly speaking, White does not need to defend his e-pawn, but he 
chooses to do so here in order to avoid any later tricks.} c5 $1 {Black must not 
be fooled by White's Knight move: the goal is still to form a broad center with 
d4 and f4. Therefore it is correct, odd as it may look, to take a grip on the d4 
square with a pawn, anticipating White's strategy and nipping his plan in the 
bud.} 6. Bc4+ $1 {This is White's only reasonable way to try to get compensation 
by ensuring that...Be6 will carry at least some cost.} Be6 {Black must be 
prepared to let his King get pulled out to e6 for a move -- but do not fear, he 
will make a rapid run back to safety.} 7. Bxe6+ {If White is not going to take 
this Bishop, his previous move makes no sense. Pulling Black's King up into the 
center is his only hope of compensation for the sacrificed material.} Kxe6 {No 
credit for other moves!} 8. d4 $1 {White reasonably hopes to open up the 
position a bit, but Black refuses to help him by capturing on d4.} Kf7 {Heading 
back toward safety. Notice that now we have the same undermining structure in 
the center that we would get in the early d4 lines -- but here, Black 
played...c5 before White got in d4.} 9. dxc5 $1 {Again, White opens what lines 
he can.} Nc6 {We have transposed back into Topalov-Kramnik, Linares 1999, which 
is the game we are following as our main line.} *

