1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 {Petroff's Defense has a reputation, not entirely deserved, 
as a stodgy drawing weapon. The truth is that only a third of all Petroff games 
that last more than 20 moves are drawn. The high percentage of short Petroff 
draws in databases reflects the willingness of both sides to sign an early peace 
treaty.} 3. Nxe5 {White has a few options to bail out into a different opening, 
but the two main moves have always been either taking the pawn or playing an 
immediate d4.} d6 {The move Nxe5!?, which is sometimes called the Damiano 
Defense, is better than its reputation, as Black does not have to fall into the 
classic trap and lose his Queen but can instead play the move as a pawn 
sacrifice. That said, d6 is the overwhelming choice at master level. It is also 
as solid as a rock.} 4. Nxf7 $5 {The Cochrane Gambit. In an era without computer 
analysis, this sort of sacrifice could terrorize would-be practitioners of the 
Petroff. Today, with both strong engines and large databases to give us a 
picture of GM praxis, it is possible to prepare against the Knight sac with 
confidence.} Kxf7 {There is no good way to decline this sacrifice, so Black 
should man up and learn the analysis required to obtain an advantage against 
it.} 5. d4 {Pushing the d-pawn immediately is White's main move and the one 
Black should study most closely. Given a few slack moves by Black, White will 
bring out a few pieces, castle, and play f4 and e5, when Black can find himself 
in quite a miserable position.} c5 $1 {The key move: Black breaks up the center 
before it can properly be formed. White's e-pawn is tactically defended, so 
Black should not be tempted to snip it off.} 6. Bc4+ $1 {This check looks 
aggressive, but Black can use a little tactical trick here:} d5 7. exd5 $1 b5 
{The point: White's Bishop must leave the a2-g8 diagonal because 8. Bb3?? would 
be met by the pawn avalanche c4 -+ winning a second piece.} 8. Bxb5 {It might 
occur to you hereabouts that White is collecting an awful lot of pawns for the 
piece. But this is the point where things turn around. White's Bishop on b5 is 
doing absolutely nothing, and suddenly Black's pieces seize quite a few nice 
open lines.} Qxd5 9. Be2 {With this retreat, White hopes to repost the Bishop on 
f3 and take advantage of the airy long diagonal. But it is Black's turn to move 
first.} Nc6 {It might seem that Black is creating some problems for himself on 
the diagonal with this move, but everything is under control.} 10. O-O {Castling 
is just too slow.} Nxd4 $19 {Black will take off the Bishop and then mobilize 
his own Bishops (probably on b7 and d6) and Rooks (on the center files), taking 
over the initiative. White has nothing remotely adequate to show for the piece.} 
*

