1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 {Petroff's Defense has a reputation, not entirely deserved, 
as a stodgy drawing weapon. The truth is that only a third of all Petroff games 
that last more than 20 moves are drawn. The high percentage of short Petroff 
draws in databases reflects the willingness of both sides to sign an early peace 
treaty.} 3. Nxe5 {White has a few options to bail out into a different opening, 
but the two main moves have always been either taking the pawn or playing an 
immediate d4.} d6 {The move Nxe5!?, which is sometimes called the Damiano 
Defense, is better than its reputation, as Black does not have to fall into the 
classic trap and lose his Queen but can instead play the move as a pawn 
sacrifice. That said, d6 is the overwhelming choice at master level. It is also 
as solid as a rock.} 4. Nxf7 $5 {The Cochrane Gambit. In an era without computer 
analysis, this sort of sacrifice could terrorize would-be practitioners of the 
Petroff. Today, with both strong engines and large databases to give us a 
picture of GM praxis, it is possible to prepare against the Knight sac with 
confidence.} Kxf7 {There is no good way to decline this sacrifice, so Black 
should man up and learn the analysis required to obtain an advantage gainst it.} 
5. d4 {Pushing the d-pawn immediately is White's main move and the one Black 
should study most closely. Given a few slack moves by Black, White will bring 
out a few pieces, castle, and play f4 and e5, when Black can find himself in 
quite a miserable position.} c5 $1 {The key move: Black breaks up the center 
before it can properly be formed. White's e-pawn is tactically defended, so 
Black should not be tempted to snip it off.} 6. dxc5 $5 Nc6 {This is a very 
ambitious way for Black to play. White hoped to be engaged in a struggle where 
he had sacrificed material for an advantage in space. Instead, Black insists on 
destroying White's big center and giving back the material in exchange for an 
advantage in time in a very unbalanced position. Black's immediate idea here 
is...Be6, after which White cannot find a decent way to drum up anything like an 
attack on the Black King.} 7. Bc4+ {White demands that the Black King be a bit 
more exposed.} Be6 {It can be difficult to tell, without a computer running or a 
database to consult, whether it is more important to keep the King back or to 
trade off potential attackers. Here, swapping off the Bishops is Black's best 
idea.} 8. Bxe6+ {White gains nothing from avoiding this exchange, as Black can 
simply exchange Bishops on d5 or b3 and complete his development in peace.} Kxe6 
{A critical position. We are following the game Topalov-Kramnik, Linares 1999. 
In the full version of this repertoire, we will explore all of White's serious 
attempts to get at the Black King.} *

